Total charges is in object form ,that can be changed to numerical.¶

SeniorCitizen is in 'int' form, that can be changed to categorical.¶

In [7]:

fig, axs = plt.subplots(ncols=3, figsize=(10,4))

# Plotting tenure distribution with churn status
axs[0].hist(df[df['Churn'] == 'No']['tenure'], bins=20, color='skyblue', alpha=0.7, label='Not Churn')
axs[0].hist(df[df['Churn'] == 'Yes']['tenure'], bins=20, color='red', alpha=0.7, label='Churn')
axs[0].set_title('Tenure Distribution')
axs[0].set_xlabel('Tenure (months)')
axs[0].set_ylabel('Frequency')
axs[0].legend()

# Plotting monthly charges distribution with churn status
axs[1].hist(df[df['Churn'] == 'No']['MonthlyCharges'], bins=20, color='skyblue', alpha=0.7, label='Not Churn')
axs[1].hist(df[df['Churn'] == 'Yes']['MonthlyCharges'], bins=20, color='red', alpha=0.7, label='Churn')
axs[1].set_title('Monthly Charges Distribution')
axs[1].set_xlabel('Monthly Charges ($)')
axs[1].set_ylabel('Frequency')
axs[1].legend()

# Plotting total charges distribution with churn status
axs[2].hist(df[df['Churn'] == 'No']['TotalCharges'], bins=20, color='skyblue', alpha=0.7, label='Not Churn')
axs[2].hist(df[df['Churn'] == 'Yes']['TotalCharges'], bins=20, color='red', alpha=0.7, label='Churn')
axs[2].set_title('Total Charges Distribution')
axs[2].set_xlabel('Total Charges ($)')
axs[2].set_ylabel('Frequency')
axs[2].legend()

In [34]:
Cus = ['gender', 'Dependents', 'Partner', 'SeniorCitizen']

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(7, 7))

for i, item in enumerate(Cus):
    if i < 2:
        ax = df[item].value_counts(normalize=True).plot(kind='bar', ax=axes[0, i], rot=0)
    elif i >= 2 and i < 4:
        ax = df[item].value_counts(normalize=True).plot(kind='bar', ax=axes[1, i-2], rot=0)
    ax.set_title(item)
    
    # Adding churn percentage to each bar plot
    for p in ax.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        ax.text(p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2., height + 0.02, '{:.2%}'.format(height), ha="center")
        
        # Adding churn percentage to each bar plot
        yes_value_counts = df[df.Churn == 'Yes'][item].value_counts(normalize=True)
        if p.get_x() in yes_value_counts.index:
            ax.text(p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2., height - 0.1, '{:.2%}'.format(yes_value_counts[p.get_x()]), ha="center")
        
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

           'OnlineBackup','DeviceProtection','TechSupport','StreamingTV','StreamingMovies']

for i in range(9):
    ax=axes[int(i/3),i%3]
    ser =services[i]
    sns.countplot(x=ser,hue='Churn',data=df,ax=ax,order=df[ser].value_counts().index)
    #present values in each bar
    for i in ax.patches:
        ax.text(i.get_x()+i.get_width()/2,i.get_height()*1,i.get_height(),color='k',

    #plt.legend(loc='best')

        ax.spines[s].set_visible(False)

import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind


# filter the data by gender
male_charges = df[df['gender'] == 'Male']['MonthlyCharges']
female_charges = df[df['gender'] == 'Female']['MonthlyCharges']

# conduct the t-test
t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(male_charges, female_charges)

# print the results
print("T-Statistic: ", t_stat)
print("P-Value: ", p_value)
#Based on the T-Statistic of -1.1554 and a p-value of 0.2479, we can conclude that there is no significant difference in the monthly charges between males and females. The p-value is greater than the standard significance level of 0.05, indicating that we cannot reject the null hypothesis that the means of the two groups are equal.

T-Statistic:  -1.155438704202737
P-Value:  0.24795008894392226

def object_to_int(dataframe_series):
    if dataframe_series.dtype=='object':
        dataframe_series = LabelEncoder().fit_transform(dataframe_series)
    return dataframe_series
